ce:section.ce:para:
A simple hydrothermal method was used to synthesize green emissive N,P-CDs using citric acid, urea, formamide, and phosphoric acid as carbon, nitrogen, and phosphor pre-sources, respectively. The TEM image of N,P-CDs was demonstrated in Fig. 1
                        a which indicated the mono-dispersed and spherical dots 5–7 nm size distribution. As shown in Fig. 1b, the maximum emission wavelength of prepared N,P-CDs is around 515 nm with an excitation wavelength of 400 nm. The absorption spectrum of prepared CDs (Fig. 1c) indicates several bands at the range of 250–650 nm, attributed to π-π* transition of sp2 domain (at 270 nm) and n-π* transitions of C = O and C = N (at 350 and 450 nm) [33,34]. The presence of N and P dopants in the structure of as-prepared CDs were confirmed by the EDS and FT-IR results (Fig. 2
                        ). According to EDS analysis, the percentage of N and P in the prepared CDs was obtained to be 52 and 9%, respectively. In addition, the functional groups including C = C (1642 cm−1), C = O (1691 cm−1), C = N (1454 cm−1), C-N (1349 cm−1), NH (1589 cm−1), P = O (1211 cm−1), P-O-C (1073 cm−1), P-OH (2500–2800 cm−1), NH2 and OH (3240–3450 cm−1) were characterized in FT-IR spectrum of N,P-CDs. Also, the appearance of the specific SPR peak of AuNPs in 520 nm confirmed the formation of AuNPs. The size of spherical AuNPs was determined around 15 nm by TEM imaging (Fig. 4b).

To achieve the maximum analytical signals, we optimized some effective factors including the amount of AuNPs and N,P-CDs, pH, buffer and Ag+ concentration, incubation time and temperature. Under the optimized condition, given in Fig. S3, (500 μL of AuNPs, pH = 11.5, 0.0375 M of glycine buffer, 4 mM of Ag+ and 100 μL of N,P-CDs) the variation in absorbance of AuNPs and fluorescence signal of N,P-CDs were proportional to uric acid in the 0.1 to10 μM and 0.5 to 10 μM concentration range, respectively (Fig. 5
                        ). The detection limit was calculated to be 40 and 400 nM for the colorimetric and fluorometric method. As showen in Fig. 5a (inset), the regression equation of colorimetric method is ΔA = 0.1073 log C + 0.1078, R2 = 0.9905, where ΔA = A-A0 is the difference between absorbance of AuNPs/Ag+ in the presence of uric acid (A) and in its absence (A0), and C is the concentration of uric acid (μM). Also, Fig. 5b (inset) indicates that the regression equation of fuolorometric method is log ΔF = 0.176 log C + 2.0325, R2 = 0.9907, where ΔF = F0-F is the difference between fluorescence of N,P-CDs/AuNPs/Ag+ in the absence of uric acid (F0) and in its presence (F), and C is the concentration of uric acid (μM). The RSD% was calculated to be 1.7% and 3.0% for the colorimetric and fluorometric method, respectively. The comparison between linear ranges and detection limits of developed dual-mode sensor and some previously reported methods indicated that our method is comparable to or better than them (Table 1
                        ).
